# short answer: no, but a lot of the high-value pieces will be — slowly, over
# decades.


# what's actually happening (2026)

# - linux kernel — accepting rust drivers since 6.1 (2022). new filesystems
#   (apple fs driver), gpu drivers (asahi, nova for nvidia), network drivers
#   showing up in rust. core kernel stays c; the *new* code increasingly isn't.
# - windows — microsoft has been rewriting parts of the nt kernel in rust
#   since ~2023 (dwritecore, parts of win32k). slow but real.
# - android — google: ~25% of new native code in android is rust, ~0
#   memory-safety cves in rust components.
# - userland tools — coreutils (uutils), sudo (sudo-rs), curl is adding rust
#   optional backends, openssh has experimental rust. many cli tools have rust
#   replacements (ripgrep, fd, bat, eza, zellij).
# - browsers — servo, parts of firefox (stylo, webrender), big chunks of
#   chromium's networking stack.
# - crypto libraries — rustls is genuinely displacing openssl in new code.
# - cloud infra — cloudflare, aws firecracker, fastly's wasm runtime, lots of
#   new infra software is born in rust.


# what's NOT getting rewritten

# - old, stable, working c — sqlite, postgres, redis core, the bsds, libc
#   itself, the gigantic mass of embedded firmware. there's no business case.
#   "if it ain't broke" applies harder when the code is 30 years old and
#   battle-tested.
# - microcontrollers below a certain size — rust is gaining, but c still
#   dominates 8 / 16-bit mcus and the long tail of vendor toolchains.
# - posix-api code — much of it is fine.
# - code where the c *is* the spec — reference implementations, abis, language
#   runtimes whose semantics are defined by the c version.


# why "no" overall

# 1. volume. estimates put the c codebase in active production at hundreds of
#    billions of lines. the rust-ecosystem economy can't rewrite that in 50
#    years even at full tilt.
# 2. incentives. memory-safety cves drive rewrites in *security-critical* code
#    (kernels, browsers, network parsers). most c code isn't security-critical
#    — it's a database engine, a codec, an embedded controller. rewrites cost
#    millions and add bugs; the roi just isn't there.
# 3. interop is the actual pattern. real-world rust usually lives *alongside*
#    c (via ffi), not as a replacement. linux, firefox, android — none are
#    "rust rewrites"; they're hybrid systems.
# 4. c has political momentum too. iso c23 shipped, c2y is in flight,
#    hardening efforts like cheri, _BitInt, [[reproducible]] annotations, and
#    bounds-checking proposals are real. c isn't a corpse waiting to be
#    replaced.


# the realistic 2030-2040 outcome

# - new security-critical systems software: mostly rust.
# - new cloud / infrastructure software: rust or go, your call.
# - new embedded on capable mcus: increasingly rust.
# - existing c: still there, still maintained, slowly absorbing rust modules
#   at the seams.
# - linux: a hybrid kernel where c is the floor and rust is the new
#   construction.


# the take

# stop thinking "rewrite" and start thinking "succession." rust is what people
# *reach for* now when they would have reached for c. that's the change. the c
# codebase isn't going anywhere — it's just going to stop growing.
